column1: All calculations were conducted on the LiDO 3 high performance cluster of TU Dortmund University. Calculations were automatically scheduled and ran on either an Intel Xeon E5-4604v4 or an Intel Xeon E5-2640v4 CPU
Geometries were generated using Maestro 2020-4/Macromodel with the OPLS3/Water force field with mixed torsional/low-mode sampling
column2: 100 steps per RB and 1000 steps max (default parameters).

column1: These conformations were then optimized using Gaussian 16revC01 with IEF-PCM using default settings for water at the B3LYP/6-311+G(d

Additional stereoisomers were treated as if they were additional conformational states of the same microstate so that for each microsate only up to 5 conformations with the lowest PCM energies for each solvent were treated with MP2/6-311+G(d
column2: p)EC-RISM using the PSE2 closure [REF1] and the resulting EC-RISM energies corrected using (c1*mu_{ex}+c2*PMV_{EC-RISM}+c3*q). The correction for water has a fixed parameter c1 = 1 since this additional parameter was found to be of no predictive value in previous challenges
column3: c2 = -0.1025 kcal*mol^-1*A^-3 and c3 = -15.7284 kcal mol^-1 e^-1. [REF2]. These yield G_{mtc} where m refers to the ionization state
column4: t to the tautomer (microstate per ionization state) and c to the respective conformation. The different statistical weights of conformations were taken into account by computing the free energy of the resulting discrete partition function G_{mt}=-RT*ln[sum_c(exp(-G_{mtc}/RT))]. For the deprotonation process of a microstate with k protons
column5: pKa_{raw}=(G_{k}-G_{k-1})/(RT ln(10)) and the macrostate pKa follows from m*pKa_{raw}+b where parameters m and b are calculated within the chosen level of theory by fitting to the reference data set from [REF3]. Here
column6: m = 0.7449 and b = -150.7196. To calculate the relative free energies with respect to each micro000
column8: depending on the difference in the protonation state. If there is no difference in the protonation state
column10: the relative free energy is calculated via m*(G(micro000)-G(m2)) to achieve thermodynamically consistent cycles. Since micro000 is always a neutral species for a single deprotonation the relative free energy is calculated using m*(G(micro000)-G(m2))+b
column11: and -(m*(G(micro000)-G(m2))+b) for a protonation process. For the doubly protonated species the calculated relative free energy is m*(G(micro000)-G(m2))+2*b
column12: and -(m*(G(micro000)-G(m2))+2*b) etc. for higher or lower protonation states [REF4]. Macrostate pKa values were calculated using the partition function approach of Eq. 5 in [REF5].

column1: The SEM was estimated as the convergence criterion for a single EC-RISM calculation. The uncertainty was estimated as the RMSE from the pKa training set.
